WEBVTT

00:06.441 --> 00:06.658
.

00:06.702 --> 00:08.965
- Previously on "Colony"...

00:09.009 --> 00:10.488
- You were using
my algorithm incorrectly.

00:10.532 --> 00:12.055
The algorithm is meaningless
if you don't apply it

00:12.099 --> 00:13.665
as it was designed.

00:13.709 --> 00:16.625
- The institute wasn't
interested in your application.

00:16.668 --> 00:18.757
What they were interested in
is your algorithm's

00:18.801 --> 00:22.152
uncanny ability to classify
the human population.

00:22.196 --> 00:24.111
- I think she's going septic.

00:24.154 --> 00:25.634
- We have to take her
to Seattle.

00:25.677 --> 00:27.070
- No.

00:27.114 --> 00:28.680
If we walk in there,
that's it for you and me.

00:28.724 --> 00:30.247
They'll ID us and arrest us.

00:30.291 --> 00:31.379
- I don't care.

00:32.902 --> 00:35.383
- Dalton, James, Laura,
and Sean.

00:35.426 --> 00:38.125
- All your answers
are being monitored,

00:38.168 --> 00:42.042
so it's important
to answer truthfully.

00:52.095 --> 00:57.883
♪

01:04.412 --> 01:07.154
- Sir, I have the Deputy Proxy
on line one.

01:07.197 --> 01:09.808
- Tell him I'm unavailable.
- Yes, sir.

01:12.594 --> 01:14.204
- Sir, now I've got
the Governor-General.

01:14.248 --> 01:16.076
He's insisting
on speaking with you.

01:16.119 --> 01:17.729
- Well, maybe he should
have called

01:17.773 --> 01:21.124
before the city literally
started burning.

01:21.168 --> 01:23.344
- I'll tell him
you're unavailable.

01:25.476 --> 01:27.870
- When the Chancellor calls,
put her through, though.

01:27.913 --> 01:30.264
- Yes, sir.

01:30.307 --> 01:31.874
[bottle uncorks
and drink pours]

01:41.536 --> 01:43.799
- Sir, Chancellor Rohner
on line one.

01:48.195 --> 01:49.239
- Camille.

01:49.283 --> 01:51.720
To what do I owe this pleasure?

01:54.810 --> 01:57.117
- You remember
the, uh, barricade scenes

01:57.160 --> 01:58.553
from "Les Mis"?

01:58.596 --> 02:01.425
It's, uh, like that,
but with bigger guns.

02:03.166 --> 02:04.472
- Of course not.

02:06.778 --> 02:09.172
- Other than going back in time
and using my algorithm

02:09.216 --> 02:10.782
the way it was intended?

02:10.826 --> 02:13.133
- I'm not calling you
to rehash the failures

02:13.176 --> 02:14.134
of the past.

02:14.177 --> 02:15.265
I'm calling for answers.

02:15.309 --> 02:17.702
- And I have them,
but first,

02:17.746 --> 02:19.443
I need to hear you say
that you've learned

02:19.487 --> 02:22.403
from your mistakes.

02:22.446 --> 02:24.100
It's possible that some

02:24.144 --> 02:26.189
of the current unrest
could have been avoided

02:26.233 --> 02:29.975
if we had paid more attention
to your proposals.

02:30.019 --> 02:32.413
- Thank you, Camille.
That's very kind of you.

02:32.456 --> 02:35.242
I'm gonna have my assistant
transfer a file to you.

02:38.941 --> 02:42.379
- It's a protocol--
a blueprint for building

02:42.423 --> 02:44.729
a model Colony here in Seattle.

02:44.773 --> 02:47.384
- You have conditions,
I assume?

02:47.428 --> 02:49.169
- Total autonomy.
No Redhats.

02:49.212 --> 02:51.214
In fact,
no Transitional Authority

02:51.258 --> 02:53.521
or IGA presence at all.

02:53.564 --> 02:54.304
- Fine.

02:54.348 --> 02:56.263
♪

02:56.306 --> 02:58.221
- And I want a meeting
with the Hosts.

02:58.265 --> 03:00.354
- Impossible.

03:00.397 --> 03:02.834
♪

03:02.878 --> 03:04.749
Why do you want
to talk to them?

03:04.793 --> 03:07.230
- Ooh, that's above
your pay grade.

03:07.274 --> 03:09.972
Or I could just
let this city burn.

03:10.015 --> 03:12.017
Wait for other cities to burn.

03:12.061 --> 03:15.369
And someday soon,
our Hosts are gonna come to you

03:15.412 --> 03:18.328
and your friends at the IGA
with questions

03:18.372 --> 03:19.764
that you can't answer.

03:21.070 --> 03:23.638
If I agree to give
you Seattle,

03:23.681 --> 03:26.902
what are you going
to do with it?

03:26.945 --> 03:30.340
- Build something beautiful.

03:30.384 --> 03:32.037
♪

03:35.084 --> 03:40.611
♪

03:45.268 --> 03:50.839
♪

03:52.536 --> 03:53.711
- I'm on the clock.

03:53.755 --> 03:55.147
♪

03:55.191 --> 03:57.759
- A man who knows his limits.

03:57.802 --> 03:58.934
How unusual.

03:58.977 --> 04:00.370
♪

04:00.414 --> 04:01.980
- I try not to make
a habit of it.

04:03.373 --> 04:05.375
- How about I buy you one
instead, Miss...

04:05.419 --> 04:08.204
- Crane.
Lillian.

04:08.248 --> 04:10.511
- James Dalton.

04:10.554 --> 04:12.730
- Well, I am not gonna turn
down another drink.

04:12.774 --> 04:14.732
But you should know
I'm married.

04:16.256 --> 04:17.387
- Afraid so.

04:17.431 --> 04:18.388
- That's a shame.

04:19.998 --> 04:22.740
- So what's a happily married
woman doing alone

04:22.784 --> 04:23.915
in a bar?

04:23.959 --> 04:26.396
- Just waiting for someone.
You?

04:26.440 --> 04:28.050
- Looking for a friend.

04:28.093 --> 04:30.444
- Hmm.

04:30.487 --> 04:32.837
An old one,
or a new one?

04:32.881 --> 04:34.274
- Old.

04:34.317 --> 04:35.710
He might have gotten himself
in some trouble.

04:35.753 --> 04:37.364
I'm trying to find him
before it gets worse.

04:37.407 --> 04:39.757
- That's nice of you.

04:39.801 --> 04:42.282
- He owes me money.

04:44.066 --> 04:46.198
- You seem like the type to
meet a lot of people.

04:46.242 --> 04:47.765
Maybe you've run into him.

04:49.419 --> 04:52.117
- Terry Lennox.

04:52.161 --> 04:54.250
He's from Spokane.
Like you.

04:57.079 --> 04:58.559
♪

04:58.602 --> 04:59.995
I'm not trying to scare you.

05:00.038 --> 05:01.605
I just need to find Terry.

05:01.649 --> 05:04.521
- I'm sorry, I haven't heard
that name in a long time.

05:04.565 --> 05:06.610
- When's the last time
you seen him?

05:06.654 --> 05:09.961
- Before, you know,
this.

05:11.267 --> 05:12.312
- Another time.

05:12.355 --> 05:13.791
♪

05:13.835 --> 05:16.620
- You don't know any other
friends of Terry's, do you?

05:16.664 --> 05:18.840
Someone who can help me?

05:18.883 --> 05:20.537
- As far as I know,
they're all dead.

05:20.581 --> 05:25.368
♪

05:26.891 --> 05:28.153
♪

05:29.198 --> 05:35.509
♪

05:37.162 --> 05:39.991
- Please leave a message for--
- Daisy Lennox.

05:40.035 --> 05:42.385
- Mrs. Lennox,
this is James Dalton.

05:42.429 --> 05:43.908
I have an update about Terry.

05:43.952 --> 05:46.476
Please give me a call
when you get this.

05:46.520 --> 05:51.351
♪

05:57.052 --> 05:58.140
Are you James?

05:58.183 --> 05:59.271
- I am.

05:59.315 --> 06:01.404
- Great.
Heading to Bellevue.

06:01.448 --> 06:03.754
- You got it.

06:04.581 --> 06:07.497
♪

06:10.108 --> 06:17.159
♪

06:42.706 --> 06:44.969
- Sounds really good.

06:45.013 --> 06:46.928
- I'm nervous.

06:46.971 --> 06:49.321
- Just talk slowly and remember
to take a deep breath

06:49.365 --> 06:51.149
before you start.

06:51.193 --> 06:52.412
You'll be good.

06:56.590 --> 07:00.289
- Hi, gang.
- Hi, Dad.

07:04.336 --> 07:06.382
I'm gonna hit the sack.

07:06.426 --> 07:08.950
Have a good day.

07:08.993 --> 07:11.909
- I cleared the Becketts
last night.

07:11.953 --> 07:13.781
Yeah, no, I know.

07:13.824 --> 07:15.347
That's all right, I'll double
check when I get back

07:15.391 --> 07:16.740
to the depot.
Okay.

07:16.784 --> 07:18.046
Yeah, I'm leaving now.

07:18.089 --> 07:19.526
♪

07:19.569 --> 07:21.615
Good morning, guys.

07:23.399 --> 07:25.836
- I wish.

07:25.880 --> 07:28.012
You're, uh, you're good
to let your sister in

07:28.056 --> 07:29.013
after school, yeah?

07:29.057 --> 07:31.581
- Yeah.

07:31.625 --> 07:34.671
- Oh, good morning, bear.

07:34.715 --> 07:36.456
Do you have a test today?

07:36.499 --> 07:38.022
- A presentation.

07:38.066 --> 07:41.504
We were supposed to go over it
last night.

07:41.548 --> 07:43.463
- Oh, bear, I'm so sorry.

07:43.506 --> 07:45.421
I--They--We had a--

07:45.465 --> 07:46.770
There was an emergency at work,

07:46.814 --> 07:50.774
and I'm sure that
you'll do great.

07:52.950 --> 07:53.734
I gotta go.

07:53.777 --> 07:56.998
I love you.
Both.

08:05.093 --> 08:08.705
- We can go over it on the way
over there, okay?

08:08.749 --> 08:12.056
Go get your stuff.
Let's go.

08:16.670 --> 08:19.150
Don't forget your phone.

08:22.893 --> 08:25.548
- All those who have received
preliminary notice

08:25.592 --> 08:28.812
of transfer, please proceed
to the bus loading zone,

08:28.856 --> 08:31.162
and wait for your name
to be called.

08:31.206 --> 08:34.383
[indistinct P.A. chatter
continues]

08:34.426 --> 08:41.390
♪

08:48.484 --> 08:50.530
- Hey, hey, hey, hey.

08:50.573 --> 08:51.705
- Over here.

08:57.058 --> 09:04.108
♪

09:14.902 --> 09:16.991
All right.

09:17.034 --> 09:18.035
Thank you.

09:18.079 --> 09:19.080
♪

09:19.123 --> 09:22.387
All right,
good morning, everybody.

09:22.431 --> 09:24.868
When I call your name,
please step forward,

09:24.912 --> 09:27.871
and then you're gonna proceed
to your designated bus.

09:27.915 --> 09:30.657
Alveraz, Ricardo.
- Yeah, here.

09:30.700 --> 09:33.747
- Here you are, bus C.
- Thank you.

09:33.790 --> 09:38.229
- And Anderson, Samantha
and Zara.

09:38.273 --> 09:41.972
Zarah
Hi!

09:42.016 --> 09:43.104
Bus A.

09:43.147 --> 09:45.410
Uh, Beckett,
Charles and Hitomi.

09:45.454 --> 09:46.586
- That's us.

09:46.629 --> 09:48.805
- Bus A.
- Thank you.

09:50.764 --> 09:52.243
Could you finish
that up for me?

09:52.287 --> 09:54.332
Thank you.

09:55.072 --> 09:56.770
Bethany, what are you
doing here?

09:57.466 --> 09:59.642
- Uh, I, uh...

09:59.686 --> 10:00.991
I didn't mean to interrupt.

10:01.035 --> 10:03.864
- You're not.
What's wrong?

10:07.476 --> 10:08.651
- There you are.

10:08.695 --> 10:09.957
Where--

10:11.175 --> 10:12.655
Mrs. Dalton.
- I'm sorry.

10:12.699 --> 10:14.918
It didn't feel right
to just leave.

10:14.962 --> 10:16.093
- It's okay, honey.

10:16.137 --> 10:17.486
- Look, I know
it's frustrating.

10:17.529 --> 10:18.661
You've gotta be patient.

10:18.705 --> 10:20.141
- We've been patient.

10:20.184 --> 10:21.490
For months.

10:21.533 --> 10:22.709
While watching other people
get waived through

10:22.752 --> 10:24.362
after a few days.

10:24.406 --> 10:26.321
- The system can only accept
so many entrants at a time

10:26.364 --> 10:29.324
and priority has to go to those
who are most vulnerable

10:29.367 --> 10:30.673
and with vital skills.

10:31.805 --> 10:34.634
- It's just time
we move on.

10:34.677 --> 10:36.940
- Okay.
Where will you go?

10:39.160 --> 10:40.291
- Another bloc.

10:40.335 --> 10:43.555
Word is they're repopulating
Los Angeles.

10:45.035 --> 10:47.908
- Just a rumor around camp.

10:47.951 --> 10:49.474
They're saying
there's no wait list,

10:49.518 --> 10:52.303
that you can just walk inside.

10:52.347 --> 10:54.958
- It's a long way
to Los Angeles.

10:55.002 --> 10:56.656
And it's dangerous.

10:56.699 --> 10:59.484
- And so is staying here.

10:59.528 --> 11:00.703
Others are going, too.

11:00.747 --> 11:02.226
Strength in numbers.

11:04.968 --> 11:07.318
- Tomorrow, first light.

11:07.362 --> 11:09.712
♪

11:20.375 --> 11:21.506
Hello?

11:21.550 --> 11:23.334
- James, it's Daisy Lennox.

11:23.378 --> 11:25.249
Uh, I--I didn't wake you up,
did I?

11:25.293 --> 11:26.903
- No, I'm up.

11:31.038 --> 11:34.432
- Hey, so, uh--so they said--
you said that--

11:34.476 --> 11:36.739
Hey, hey, settle--settle down.

11:36.783 --> 11:39.089
Oh, I'm sorry.
- It's okay.

11:39.133 --> 11:43.790
- Um, so, uh, you were saying
you have an update about Terry?

11:43.833 --> 11:45.095
- Yeah.

11:45.139 --> 11:46.706
There's no record
of your husband

11:46.749 --> 11:48.751
ever entering the Colony.

11:48.795 --> 11:50.057
- Well, I don't
understand that.

11:50.100 --> 11:52.189
He got into the colony
four months ago.

11:52.233 --> 11:54.496
I-I watched him walk into
the processing tent.

11:54.539 --> 11:55.671
- I had a friend run his name.

11:55.715 --> 11:57.064
Came back with nothing.

11:57.107 --> 11:59.675
- But Dylan saw him inside.

11:59.719 --> 12:00.937
- I checked into it.

12:00.981 --> 12:02.591
There aren't any cameras
at the school.

12:02.634 --> 12:05.376
- You're saying he wouldn't
recognize his own father?

12:05.420 --> 12:07.378
- Look, I believe you.

12:07.422 --> 12:08.989
And him.

12:09.032 --> 12:10.773
Which is why I've been looking
into the list of names

12:10.817 --> 12:11.992
you gave me.

12:12.035 --> 12:12.993
So far,
I've only been able

12:13.036 --> 12:14.690
to trace one of them.

12:14.734 --> 12:17.258
Lillian Crane?

12:17.954 --> 12:20.565
She was part of your group
after the Arrival?

12:20.609 --> 12:24.221
- Um, yeah, her and
her husband, Jonathan.

12:25.092 --> 12:26.528
- They're here now,
living over

12:26.571 --> 12:27.747
in the Bellevue bloc.

12:29.400 --> 12:32.882
Well, that's just like them,
to land on their feet.

12:32.926 --> 12:35.580
- How well did you
know the Cranes?

12:35.624 --> 12:37.104
Not well.

12:37.147 --> 12:40.455
Lillian didn't need anybody
who wasn't in her tax bracket.

12:40.498 --> 12:43.763
Not even the end of the world
seemed to change that.

12:45.721 --> 12:48.855
- Oh, he was Terry's
boss at Boeing.

12:50.073 --> 12:53.163
- Someone Terry might
go to for help?

12:53.207 --> 12:55.296
- Maybe.

12:55.339 --> 12:56.427
I don't understand.

12:56.471 --> 12:58.255
How can it be so hard
to find someone?

12:58.299 --> 13:00.649
We're locked in a city
surrounded by giant walls.

13:00.692 --> 13:02.869
- If I had a photo,
I could track him in a week.

13:02.912 --> 13:04.305
But it's not that easy.

13:07.743 --> 13:12.052
A lot of people have
disappeared in this colony.

13:15.316 --> 13:19.929
♪

13:19.973 --> 13:22.889
There are cases
like your husband--

13:22.932 --> 13:25.543
Engineers, doctors, soldiers--
being taken.

13:25.587 --> 13:26.893
♪

13:26.936 --> 13:29.547
- Taken--
- Abducted.

13:29.591 --> 13:31.071
♪

13:33.247 --> 13:36.032
- That's what I'm trying
to find out.

13:36.076 --> 13:37.686
Did Terry have
any other skills?

13:37.729 --> 13:39.253
A hobby?

13:39.296 --> 13:42.822
Something he could do off
the grid to stay afloat?

13:42.865 --> 13:45.389
- Uh...

13:45.433 --> 13:46.956
I don't know, uh...

13:47.000 --> 13:49.916
He likes old cars,
fixing them.

13:49.959 --> 13:51.656
Like old Chevys and Fords.

13:51.700 --> 13:54.398
♪

13:54.442 --> 13:56.661
Please, I need to know
what happened to him.

13:56.705 --> 13:58.881
♪

13:58.925 --> 14:01.492
- If Terry's in this colony,
I'll find him.

14:01.536 --> 14:03.407
I promise.

14:03.451 --> 14:06.933
I'll be in touch.

14:29.956 --> 14:30.173
.

14:32.088 --> 14:33.524
- I don't know.

14:33.568 --> 14:35.135
I may have to cover
for my parents again.

14:35.178 --> 14:39.095
- That's some kind of bullshit.
- Tell me about it.

14:46.929 --> 14:49.671
Ms. Frazetta?
Your allocation.

15:07.471 --> 15:09.212
- It's all there.
Thanks.

15:09.256 --> 15:10.648
- Have a good one.

15:12.041 --> 15:13.347
- I've been meaning
to tell you.

15:13.390 --> 15:14.652
I'm quitting this gig.

15:15.610 --> 15:17.307
- You got something
else lined up?

15:17.351 --> 15:19.483
- Community patrol, I think.

15:20.963 --> 15:22.573
- Yeah, well, it beats
being the pizza man.

15:22.617 --> 15:24.401
And I hear you qualify
for better housing.

15:24.445 --> 15:25.794
Maybe even a car.

15:59.480 --> 16:01.395
- I'm James Dalton.

16:01.438 --> 16:04.528
Here about Terry Lennox.

16:20.936 --> 16:23.852
- Nice place.
What do you do?

16:23.895 --> 16:27.290
- I work for
the Seattle Initiative.

16:27.334 --> 16:29.466
- Same kind of thing you were
doing for Boeing?

16:29.510 --> 16:32.165
- That's classified.

16:32.208 --> 16:34.776
Why are you here?

16:34.819 --> 16:37.300
- Terry Lennox came through
screening into the colony

16:37.344 --> 16:38.693
and then disappeared.

16:38.736 --> 16:40.869
- And you think I know
where he is?

16:40.912 --> 16:42.131
- Just taking shots
in the dark,

16:42.175 --> 16:44.699
looking for anyone
who knew him.

16:44.742 --> 16:48.181
- Out of the kindness
of your heart?

16:48.224 --> 16:50.139
- I was hired to find him.

16:50.183 --> 16:53.490
Like a private detective?

16:53.534 --> 16:54.926
By who?

16:54.970 --> 16:57.494
- His wife.
You knew her?

16:57.538 --> 17:00.323
- Yeah.

17:00.367 --> 17:02.673
Talked a lot.

17:02.717 --> 17:05.198
Mmm, kinda hard to be around.

17:06.373 --> 17:08.157
- She's on her own now.

17:08.201 --> 17:10.159
With kids.

17:10.203 --> 17:12.553
- That's too bad.

17:17.340 --> 17:19.168
- He worked for me.

17:21.692 --> 17:24.347
- One of the best.

17:24.391 --> 17:26.132
- I heard he liked
classic cars.

17:27.524 --> 17:30.658
- Not really my thing.

17:35.097 --> 17:38.013
- After the Arrival.

17:38.057 --> 17:41.886
Group of us were outside the
walls just trying to survive.

17:41.930 --> 17:45.760
One night,
a bunch of walkers showed up.

17:46.761 --> 17:48.806
Tore right through us.

17:50.156 --> 17:52.201
My wife and I managed
to escape.

17:52.245 --> 17:55.900
Honestly, I figured Terry
and his family were dead.

17:55.944 --> 17:57.554
- And you haven't
seen him since?

17:57.598 --> 18:00.209
- No.

18:00.253 --> 18:03.125
- I don't suppose you'd be
hiding him in your basement?

18:04.605 --> 18:06.172
- Sorry.

18:06.215 --> 18:08.826
- Would have made my life
a lot easier.

18:08.870 --> 18:10.959
- Tell me something.

18:11.002 --> 18:13.135
If Terry really made it
to Seattle,

18:13.179 --> 18:15.137
what do you think
happened to him?

18:15.181 --> 18:17.400
- He was taken
by the Occupation.

18:19.228 --> 18:21.883
What would the Occupation
want with him?

18:21.926 --> 18:24.538
- I figure that out...

18:24.581 --> 18:27.106
We'll be a long way
to finding him.

18:27.149 --> 18:29.804
If you hear anything,
I'd appreciate a call.

18:30.805 --> 18:33.112
Thanks for your time.

18:39.814 --> 18:42.469
- Another 120 arrivals.

18:42.512 --> 18:44.079
No rest for the wicked.

18:44.123 --> 18:46.255
How'd this morning's intake go?

18:46.299 --> 18:47.691
- Fine.

18:49.998 --> 18:52.000
- It's one of my families.
They're tier two.

18:52.043 --> 18:53.741
They've been stuck in the camps
for four months

18:53.784 --> 18:55.525
getting frustrated,
and now they wanna leave.

18:55.569 --> 18:56.787
- Well, that's
their prerogative.

18:56.831 --> 18:59.877
- Yeah, but they're so close.

18:59.921 --> 19:01.444
What if something happens
to them out there?

19:01.488 --> 19:03.533
- You can't get personally
attached to every family

19:03.577 --> 19:04.795
that crosses your desk, Laura.

19:04.839 --> 19:07.146
- I know.
They've been through a lot.

19:07.189 --> 19:09.148
They lost their five-year-old
on the road.

19:15.850 --> 19:17.634
There's gotta be some way
to push them up the list.

19:17.678 --> 19:19.201
- Well, a list is a list.

19:19.245 --> 19:22.465
I mean, once you're on it,
all you can do is wait.

19:22.509 --> 19:25.033
Unless...

19:25.076 --> 19:27.209
Maybe you missed something
in the first interview.

19:27.253 --> 19:29.124
♪

19:29.168 --> 19:30.299
- You know,
I think you're right.

19:30.343 --> 19:32.083
I might have been rushing.

19:32.127 --> 19:34.347
- I think you should do
a supplemental one.

19:34.390 --> 19:35.478
Just in case.

19:35.522 --> 19:37.437
♪

19:37.480 --> 19:38.873
You know, for what it's worth,

19:38.916 --> 19:40.657
I hear they're prioritizing
skilled laborers

19:40.701 --> 19:41.745
in the current intake.

19:41.789 --> 19:47.273
♪

19:47.316 --> 19:50.754
- Mr. and Mrs. Winslow,
thank you for coming back in.

19:50.798 --> 19:53.757
- Um, I'm afraid you're
wasting your time.

19:53.801 --> 19:55.498
We're leaving in the morning.

19:55.542 --> 19:58.501
- That's not why
I asked you back.

19:58.545 --> 20:01.200
I need to apologize.

20:02.375 --> 20:03.854
- There was an error.

20:03.898 --> 20:06.422
Some parts of your application
were left incomplete.

20:07.728 --> 20:10.426
- Employment history,
primarily.

20:10.470 --> 20:15.257
Tell me, Frank, have you ever
worked any construction?

20:18.565 --> 20:18.956
.

20:21.089 --> 20:22.221
- Okay.

20:22.264 --> 20:23.961
Viola Day kept trying
to mess me up

20:24.005 --> 20:25.528
by asking dumb questions.

20:27.095 --> 20:29.706
What about Earth Sciences?

20:29.750 --> 20:31.708
Ms. Cabot?

20:31.752 --> 20:33.493
- Mrs. Cable.

20:33.536 --> 20:35.799
She's teaching us physics.

20:35.843 --> 20:37.105
Like how for every action

20:37.148 --> 20:39.150
there's an equal
and opposite reaction.

20:39.194 --> 20:40.978
- Aren't you a little young
to be learning physics?

20:41.022 --> 20:44.721
I didn't get into that until
high school, I think.

20:44.765 --> 20:46.854
- Things are different.

20:46.897 --> 20:47.985
- I guess so.

20:50.074 --> 20:52.251
Why don't we go out
for dinner tonight?

20:52.294 --> 20:54.253
Anywhere you want.

20:56.342 --> 20:58.822
- They have to host
that neighborhood thing.

21:03.392 --> 21:06.003
- Do you think they're gonna
get a divorce?

21:09.703 --> 21:12.140
- I don't know.

21:15.839 --> 21:19.278
- Come on.
Let's go.

21:28.112 --> 21:29.766
- The Winslows have been
reallocated to tier one

21:29.810 --> 21:31.202
and have priority entry.

21:31.246 --> 21:32.726
They're already on their way
to the depot.

21:32.769 --> 21:33.944
If you hurry,
you might catch them.

21:33.988 --> 21:37.121
♪

21:37.165 --> 21:39.428
- Thank you.
- You're welcome.

21:39.472 --> 21:40.951
- Krauss, Risa.

21:40.995 --> 21:42.736
- That's me.

21:42.779 --> 21:45.173
- Hey!
I thought I'd missed you.

21:45.216 --> 21:46.957
- They told us
to come straight here.

21:47.001 --> 21:48.002
- I still can't believe it.

21:48.045 --> 21:49.133
How did you--

21:49.177 --> 21:50.396
- Well, it might mean you have

21:50.439 --> 21:52.136
to spend a few months
hauling bricks.

21:52.180 --> 21:53.790
I figured you'd be
okay with that.

21:53.834 --> 21:55.314
Yes, ma'am.

21:55.357 --> 21:56.880
- Did they tell you
what bus you're on?

21:56.924 --> 21:58.229
- They said D.

21:58.273 --> 22:01.798
- Winslow--Bethany,
Erin, and Frank.

22:01.842 --> 22:03.365
- That's us.

22:03.409 --> 22:05.454
- If you have received
preliminary notice...

22:05.498 --> 22:07.326
- Oh, thank you so much.

22:10.807 --> 22:12.679
♪

22:12.722 --> 22:13.897
Thank you.

22:13.941 --> 22:16.378
- Green, Jason and Alex.
Green.

22:16.422 --> 22:19.120
- That's us.
- Jason and Alex.

22:19.163 --> 22:22.079
- Yeah, we're here.
- Here!

22:22.123 --> 22:27.302
♪

22:41.708 --> 22:42.665
- It is now.

22:42.709 --> 22:43.927
Used to be a chop shop.

22:43.971 --> 22:46.452
We all get second chances,
I guess.

22:46.495 --> 22:47.844
You looking for a car?

22:47.888 --> 22:49.498
- Actually, I'm here
about a mechanic.

22:49.542 --> 22:50.760
A guy named Terry Lennox.

22:50.804 --> 22:52.675
Might have come in
looking for work.

22:52.719 --> 22:54.155
- Doesn't sound familiar.

22:56.070 --> 22:58.202
- Hell of a collection.

22:58.246 --> 22:59.856
People actually still
drive these things?

22:59.900 --> 23:02.206
- Yep.

23:02.250 --> 23:05.340
- Hard to believe, you know,
the world the way it is.

23:06.559 --> 23:08.909
Don't suppose you had
any old Chevys or Fords

23:08.952 --> 23:10.998
come through here recently?

23:11.041 --> 23:14.218
Maybe mid

23:14.262 --> 23:16.525
- Yeah, actually, we had a real
beauty come through

23:16.569 --> 23:17.526
a few months ago.

23:17.570 --> 23:18.788
A blue Corvette.

23:18.832 --> 23:21.400
Matching numbers
and everything.

23:21.443 --> 23:23.227
Mechanically, she was
in great shape.

23:23.271 --> 23:24.751
Just did a refresh job.

23:24.794 --> 23:26.970
New brakes, lines, fluids.

23:28.058 --> 23:29.451
- Couldn't tell you.

23:29.495 --> 23:32.976
Got a better memory
for cars than people.

23:34.325 --> 23:36.980
Was a...

23:37.024 --> 23:39.113
Boy, girl?
Black, white?

23:39.156 --> 23:40.854
- Well, it was a guy.

23:40.897 --> 23:42.812
White.

23:42.856 --> 23:43.813
He was bald.

23:43.857 --> 23:45.511
♪

23:47.817 --> 23:50.385
- Maybe.

23:50.429 --> 23:51.778
Yeah, yeah.

23:51.821 --> 23:53.649
♪

23:55.129 --> 23:56.086
- ♪ Well, he must have--

23:59.916 --> 24:01.483
- Jesus.

24:01.527 --> 24:03.224
What the hell
are you doing here?

24:03.267 --> 24:06.140
- Heard about your car.
Came to check it out.

24:06.183 --> 24:07.750
It's beautiful.

24:07.794 --> 24:10.927
Guess that's just one of the
perks of being Jonathan Crane.

24:10.971 --> 24:12.015
Isn't it, Terry?

24:12.059 --> 24:13.974
♪

24:14.017 --> 24:17.281
Man can change his name,
change the way he looks,

24:17.325 --> 24:19.762
but he can't change
who he really is.

24:19.806 --> 24:21.285
- Get off my property.

24:21.329 --> 24:23.374
- I wanna know how
you can live with yourself.

24:23.418 --> 24:26.421
Walked out on your wife
and kids for what?

24:26.465 --> 24:28.771
Nice car,
fancy house,

24:28.815 --> 24:29.816
piece of ass.

24:29.859 --> 24:31.992
- Her name is Lillian.

24:32.035 --> 24:34.298
And we were supposed
to be together.

24:34.342 --> 24:37.606
We were making plans
when it happened.

24:37.650 --> 24:39.390
I thought I'd lost her.

24:39.434 --> 24:41.741
Seattle lets you start over.

24:41.784 --> 24:44.483
- While your wife and kids get
to live through a nightmare.

24:44.526 --> 24:45.875
- I did my job!

24:45.919 --> 24:47.137
I got them inside.

24:47.181 --> 24:50.880
- Yeah, you're a real hero.

24:50.924 --> 24:53.796
- I don't have to explain
myself to you.

24:53.840 --> 24:55.450
If I tell the Initiative
about this--

24:55.494 --> 24:56.582
- Go ahead.

24:56.625 --> 24:58.497
I'm sure the bosses
would love to hear

24:58.540 --> 25:01.717
about your messy personal life.

25:06.113 --> 25:07.331
What are you gonna
do with that?

25:07.375 --> 25:09.464
- Get out!

25:09.508 --> 25:11.945
- No.

25:11.988 --> 25:14.164
I'm the only one
who knows your secret.

25:14.208 --> 25:17.167
Can be like this conversation
never happened.

25:17.211 --> 25:18.952
All you've gotta do
is hit me.

25:18.995 --> 25:20.693
♪

25:20.736 --> 25:23.478
Come on, do it,
you piece of shit.

25:23.522 --> 25:24.348
Come on.

25:24.392 --> 25:27.526
Hit me!
Hit me!

25:30.572 --> 25:37.536
♪

25:50.636 --> 25:57.643
♪

26:11.439 --> 26:13.833
- What are you--
- He got what he deserved.

26:48.389 --> 26:48.563
.

26:48.607 --> 26:50.565
- There you are.

26:50.609 --> 26:52.132
We're gonna have a house full
of people in half an hour.

26:52.175 --> 26:53.786
- Give me two minutes.

26:53.829 --> 26:55.657
- You know how important
these things are.

26:55.701 --> 26:57.746
People notice...

27:00.793 --> 27:07.843
♪

27:09.453 --> 27:12.543
Hi, please excuse me.

27:12.587 --> 27:14.328
You remember my husband, James?

27:14.371 --> 27:16.025
- Of course.
It's good to see you again.

27:16.069 --> 27:17.331
- You, too.

27:17.374 --> 27:18.811
- It's a lovely home.

27:18.854 --> 27:20.160
- Thank you.

27:20.203 --> 27:21.204
My wife has nothing
but good things

27:21.248 --> 27:22.336
to say about you.

27:22.379 --> 27:23.729
I'm getting a little jealous.

27:23.772 --> 27:26.775
How about a drink?
- Yes, yes.

27:36.437 --> 27:39.614
Everybody, good evening.

27:42.182 --> 27:44.706
As you all know,
we are here tonight

27:44.750 --> 27:48.797
to welcome our new local
community patrol captain,

27:48.841 --> 27:49.929
Roger Erikson.

27:51.365 --> 27:53.846
- Thank you.
Thank you, Laura.

27:53.889 --> 27:57.676
It is an honor to serve all
of you and ensure your safety.

27:58.415 --> 27:59.590
By watching out for each other,

27:59.634 --> 28:01.462
and supporting the patrol,

28:01.505 --> 28:03.812
together we can build
the right kind of community

28:03.856 --> 28:04.813
for our families.

28:05.901 --> 28:08.425
- Well said.

28:10.427 --> 28:11.472
- Thank you for hosting this.

28:11.515 --> 28:13.387
- It's my pleasure, really.

28:13.430 --> 28:15.215
- Michelle tells me that you
are one of her Advocates.

28:15.258 --> 28:16.564
- I am.

28:16.607 --> 28:18.348
- Tough work, but rewarding,
I'm sure.

28:18.392 --> 28:20.568
- It is.
Very.

28:20.611 --> 28:22.831
People are looking
for a sanctuary.

28:22.875 --> 28:24.615
And thanks to
the Community Patrol,

28:24.659 --> 28:26.966
they can find one in Seattle.

28:27.009 --> 28:29.403
This is my husband, James.

28:29.446 --> 28:31.057
- Glad to meet you.
Are you an Advocate, too?

28:31.100 --> 28:33.973
- No, the city's already
too crowded for my taste.

28:35.714 --> 28:38.238
- Have you given any thought
to joining Community Patrol?

28:38.281 --> 28:40.370
I hear they're looking
for good men.

28:40.414 --> 28:42.503
- Law enforcement isn't
really my thing.

28:42.546 --> 28:43.983
Nice uniforms, though.

28:46.681 --> 28:48.901
- Well, I should do the rounds.

28:48.944 --> 28:50.903
Thank you again for hosting.
- Mm-hmm.

28:50.946 --> 28:53.732
♪

28:53.775 --> 28:55.211
- Ladies.

28:55.255 --> 29:02.479
♪

29:23.587 --> 29:26.590
- Oh, sorry.
I was looking for the bathroom.

29:26.634 --> 29:28.592
- It's downstairs.

29:28.636 --> 29:30.290
- Laura throws a hell
of a party.

29:30.333 --> 29:32.205
She really seems to be
enjoying herself.

29:32.248 --> 29:33.206
- Good for her.

29:33.249 --> 29:34.816
♪

29:34.860 --> 29:36.035
- She deserves it.

29:36.078 --> 29:37.863
Does Laura tell you about
the work she does

29:37.906 --> 29:40.779
at the refugee camp?

29:40.822 --> 29:42.824
- No offense, Michelle,
but I like to keep

29:42.868 --> 29:45.522
my private conversations
private.

29:47.133 --> 29:49.700
- I--

29:49.744 --> 29:51.485
- I'm gonna get
a refill.

29:51.528 --> 29:55.315
- You know, James,
Laura's my friend.

29:55.358 --> 29:57.056
I just want her
to be happy.

29:57.099 --> 29:58.666
- So do I.

30:00.059 --> 30:02.409
- You know, most people who get
a second chance at life,

30:02.452 --> 30:04.454
they grab on to it.

30:04.498 --> 30:06.326
You don't have
to like this place,

30:06.369 --> 30:08.415
but for Laura's sake,

30:08.458 --> 30:11.070
I suggest you work a little
harder to fit in.

30:11.113 --> 30:12.854
People are always watching.

30:12.898 --> 30:16.075
- Like your friend,
Captain Roger Erikson?

30:16.118 --> 30:17.424
♪

30:17.467 --> 30:19.513
- He's a good man.

30:19.556 --> 30:22.603
- Thanks for the advice.

30:22.646 --> 30:29.828
♪

30:31.046 --> 30:38.053
♪

30:48.281 --> 30:48.498
.

30:52.415 --> 30:54.853
I asked for one night.

30:54.896 --> 30:56.289
Just one goddamn night.

30:56.332 --> 30:57.899
- You know I didn't want
to host that thing.

30:57.943 --> 30:59.118
- You didn't.

30:59.161 --> 31:00.597
I planned it,
did the shopping,

31:00.641 --> 31:02.034
cleaned the house--

31:02.077 --> 31:04.384
- Yeah, Michelle said you threw
a hell of a party.

31:05.951 --> 31:09.215
- These things aren't optional.
It was our turn to host.

31:09.258 --> 31:11.913
There are expectations that
come with living here.

31:11.957 --> 31:13.219
Rules to follow.

31:13.262 --> 31:14.829
- And suddenly you're
okay with that?

31:14.873 --> 31:17.484
- If it means we're safe.

31:17.527 --> 31:20.922
It means our kids have
a school to go to

31:20.966 --> 31:22.793
and a job.

31:22.837 --> 31:25.492
This place may not be perfect,
but we could have a life here.

31:25.535 --> 31:27.233
Except for some reason,
you seem determined

31:27.276 --> 31:28.974
to tear it all down.

31:29.017 --> 31:31.933
- This place may have cars and
phones and a Community Patrol

31:31.977 --> 31:32.934
instead of Redhats,

31:32.978 --> 31:33.935
but it's still a Colony.

31:33.979 --> 31:35.241
- And we signed up for it.

31:35.284 --> 31:36.329
- Doesn't mean I have
to like it.

31:37.678 --> 31:39.288
This is as good
as it's gonna get.

31:41.247 --> 31:43.379
- That's not the Katie Bowman
I knew in L.A.

31:46.034 --> 31:49.081
- I left that behind.

31:49.124 --> 31:55.522
♪

31:55.565 --> 31:57.959
You gotta stop punishing
yourself, Will.

31:58.003 --> 31:59.308
Give this place a chance.

31:59.352 --> 32:02.485
♪

32:02.529 --> 32:04.052
Do I even wanna know
what you've been doing

32:04.096 --> 32:05.097
with your nights?

32:05.140 --> 32:06.968
♪

32:07.012 --> 32:08.013
- No.

32:08.056 --> 32:13.888
♪

32:13.932 --> 32:15.107
- I'm listening.

32:15.150 --> 32:21.983
♪

32:22.027 --> 32:23.942
Where are you going?
- Out.

32:23.985 --> 32:28.120
♪

32:28.163 --> 32:29.295
- We aren't finished.

32:29.338 --> 32:30.818
- Yeah, we are.

32:30.861 --> 32:34.648
♪

32:34.691 --> 32:35.736
- Damn it.

32:35.779 --> 32:39.174
♪

32:39.218 --> 32:40.654
I'm sorry.

32:40.697 --> 32:42.830
♪

32:42.873 --> 32:44.832
Thank you for your help
with your sister.

32:44.875 --> 32:49.010
I know we've been leaning
really hard on you lately.

32:49.054 --> 32:50.011
- It's fine.

32:50.055 --> 32:52.144
♪

32:54.624 --> 32:56.235
- I have to run some
overnight deliveries,

32:56.278 --> 32:58.237
but I'll be back in time
to bring Gracie to school.

32:58.280 --> 32:59.499
♪

32:59.542 --> 33:01.109
- Proud of you,
you know that?

33:01.153 --> 33:02.676
♪

33:03.764 --> 33:04.721
Don't work too hard.

33:04.765 --> 33:11.815
♪

33:34.099 --> 33:36.057
- Hey, man.

33:36.101 --> 33:38.059
Yo, you bring it?
- Yeah.

33:41.106 --> 33:42.194
♪

33:42.237 --> 33:44.674
- Let's get this party going!

33:44.718 --> 33:50.637
♪

33:50.680 --> 33:52.204
- You don't always have to be
the one to bring the booze,

33:52.247 --> 33:53.596
you know.

33:53.640 --> 33:56.077
- I do if I wanna keep
getting invited.

33:56.121 --> 33:57.644
- I never bring anything.

33:57.687 --> 33:59.950
- That's 'cause the rules for
girls are different.

33:59.994 --> 34:01.822
Especially pretty ones.

34:01.865 --> 34:08.829
♪

34:09.917 --> 34:11.223
- Yeah.

34:12.833 --> 34:14.095
- The same.

34:14.139 --> 34:15.705
- Sorry.

34:15.749 --> 34:18.230
♪

34:18.273 --> 34:21.233
My parents were asking
about you.

34:21.276 --> 34:22.712
- I guess I made a good
impression.

34:22.756 --> 34:25.411
Don't get cocky.

34:25.454 --> 34:28.414
My dad ran off my last
three boyfriends.

34:31.286 --> 34:32.244
Come on.

34:32.287 --> 34:35.812
♪

34:53.308 --> 34:56.006
- Good morning Mr., uh, Dalton.

34:57.225 --> 34:58.487
Everything okay?

34:59.184 --> 35:00.620
- Everything's fine, officer.

35:00.663 --> 35:01.969
I was working the night shift.

35:02.012 --> 35:03.579
Got a little drowsy.

35:03.623 --> 35:05.668
- Your phone log states you've
been in this spot

35:05.712 --> 35:07.453
since a little after 1:00 a.m.

35:08.367 --> 35:10.369
- Must have slept longer
than I thought.

35:10.412 --> 35:11.979
Should be heading home.

35:12.022 --> 35:13.589
- Yes, you should.

35:52.889 --> 35:55.675
♪

35:55.718 --> 35:57.198
- Hey, Michelle,
do you have a minute?

35:57.242 --> 35:58.678
- Oh, yeah.
What's up?

35:58.721 --> 36:00.070
- Thank you for your help
with the Winslows.

36:00.114 --> 36:01.594
- Oh, it's no problem.

36:01.637 --> 36:03.509
- I know I should let it go,
but I kinda need to know

36:03.552 --> 36:04.901
how they're doing.

36:04.945 --> 36:06.903
- Oh, you know,
that's not the job.

36:06.947 --> 36:09.079
You're gonna have to keep
some separation, Laura,

36:09.123 --> 36:10.472
or you're gonna burn out.

36:10.516 --> 36:13.388
I don't wanna lose
another good advocate.

36:13.432 --> 36:14.520
- I get it.

36:14.563 --> 36:15.869
I just felt connected to them.

36:15.912 --> 36:17.697
And I wanna know
that they landed safely.

36:17.740 --> 36:19.655
- Of course they did.

36:21.353 --> 36:22.658
- In one of the public
housing blocs.

36:23.703 --> 36:24.878
I know it sounds stupid.

36:24.921 --> 36:26.923
I just need it
to feel tangible.

36:31.667 --> 36:37.325
♪

36:37.369 --> 36:40.589
Seattle address.

36:40.633 --> 36:42.069
They're fine, Laura.

36:42.112 --> 36:43.244
♪

36:43.288 --> 36:44.245
- Thank you.

36:44.289 --> 36:51.557
♪

37:29.247 --> 37:36.471
♪

38:02.845 --> 38:03.237
.

38:03.281 --> 38:05.239
- This is impressive.

38:05.283 --> 38:07.328
Excellent metrics from all
three of your placements.

38:07.372 --> 38:09.417
You have any idea of
what you wanna do next?

38:09.461 --> 38:11.724
- I heard that some jobs
come with special benefits.

38:11.767 --> 38:14.466
- Some, yes, though it's mainly
highly skilled positions

38:14.509 --> 38:16.076
in select areas.

38:16.119 --> 38:18.600
There are, however, allowances
for jobs that are beneficial

38:18.644 --> 38:19.862
to the community.

38:19.906 --> 38:21.299
Are you interested
in one of those?

38:22.474 --> 38:23.518
- Sure.

38:26.521 --> 38:29.350
- This is a safe space,
Mr. Dalton.

38:29.394 --> 38:31.352
It'll be easier for me
to do my job

38:31.396 --> 38:33.398
if you tell me what you want.

38:39.360 --> 38:41.319
- I have a younger sister.

38:41.362 --> 38:43.233
And we're living with my
parents right now,

38:43.277 --> 38:45.714
but I want my own place.

38:45.758 --> 38:48.543
In case something happens

38:48.587 --> 38:51.067
and I have to
look out for her.

38:51.111 --> 38:52.373
- Of course.

38:52.417 --> 38:54.332
Let me see what I can do
to help you.

38:59.162 --> 39:02.557
♪

39:02.601 --> 39:05.560
- Sorry, the boys were up
half the night.

39:05.604 --> 39:08.302
Can I get you a cup
of coffee?

39:08.346 --> 39:09.869
- No, no, I'm okay.

39:09.912 --> 39:12.524
♪

39:13.960 --> 39:16.136
You found something.

39:23.665 --> 39:26.407
Please, just tell me.

39:29.454 --> 39:33.196
- I'm sorry,
but your husband is dead.

39:38.811 --> 39:42.336
- Heart attack just after
he was admitted to the colony.

39:42.380 --> 39:47.167
♪

39:48.995 --> 39:52.259
♪

39:52.302 --> 39:54.609
- I'm sure.

39:54.653 --> 39:56.132
♪

39:59.005 --> 40:01.834
But he was so--
he was so young.

40:01.877 --> 40:03.139
- Happens a lot these days.

40:03.183 --> 40:04.837
The stress.

40:04.880 --> 40:06.534
- Okay, well, what about
the things that you

40:06.578 --> 40:08.144
were telling me--
the conspiracy,

40:08.188 --> 40:09.363
the people being abducted.

40:09.407 --> 40:11.278
- I was wrong.

40:11.321 --> 40:13.933
Whoever your boy saw that day,
it wasn't Terry.

40:13.976 --> 40:16.892
♪

40:18.807 --> 40:20.809
At least I know what
to tell the boys.

40:20.853 --> 40:24.465
♪

40:24.509 --> 40:26.075
I'll, uh--
I'll get your payment.

40:26.119 --> 40:27.163
- Keep it.

40:27.207 --> 40:28.774
♪

40:28.817 --> 40:31.037
You have to build
a new life now.

40:31.080 --> 40:32.168
You're gonna need it.

40:32.212 --> 40:39.437
♪

41:07.639 --> 41:08.727
Off duty.

41:10.119 --> 41:11.251
Get out of the damn car.

41:11.947 --> 41:13.993
- Is that any way to greet
an old friend?

41:14.036 --> 41:16.517
♪

41:16.561 --> 41:18.954
You're a hard man to find,
Mr. Dalton.

41:18.998 --> 41:20.565
♪

41:20.608 --> 41:21.957
- What the hell
are you doing here?

41:22.001 --> 41:24.220
♪

41:24.264 --> 41:26.222
- Seattle's an interesting
city.

41:26.266 --> 41:27.659
♪

41:27.702 --> 41:30.923
Wanted to know what you
make of the place.
